& NEW YORK. July 22 George H.\nBred. Captain of America's fencing\nteam in the Olympic games, today\nannounced the final makeup of the\nn am, which Includes four men from\nJHn the army and five of the navy, Pro\nfessor of the Darrlculat. fencing mas\nter at the Washington fencers' club.\nff.' I will accompany the team as couch\nand Instructor\nMy The team consists of'\nLieutenant Colonel Robert Seers,\nEM captain Harold M. Ranor. major W.\nF. Honeycutt, Sergeant John W, Hi\nmond. Henry Breckenridge. fnsign E.\nG Full lm. eider. R. L Bowman. C. J.\nWalker and F J. t 'unningham. Will- i\nlain H. RlMEOll, Boston, J. Brooks,\nB. Parker. Philadelphia, Ra W\nDutcher, New York; Arthur S. LyonJ\nI New York; George n. Breed, .New\nYork (Captain), Leon M, Schomaker,\nI New York; Dr Ernest J Gignoux.\nNew \"iork and C. Brandon Fraley,\nPhiladelphia.\nAMERICAN TRAPSHOTS\nCONTINUE GOOD WORK\ni\nANTWERP, JuK :c The Ameri\ncan trapshooilnK team m the Olympic\ncompetition today losed Its shooting\n'In the teum match hero with a total\nI of M7 turK'-ts out of a possible 000\nThe Individual American bcorcs out of\na possible 100 were'\nFrank If, Troeh, Vancouver, Wash..\n04; Mark Uric, Champagne, 111., at i\nHorace Bonier, Cincinnati, J3 FOresti\nW McNIer, Houston. Tex.. 93. Frank\nS Wright. Buffalo, N. Y- 89 Jay\nClark, Jr Worcester, Mass.. 84. Total.\n547.\nTroch shot the last thirty targets\nwith a severely cut trlKj?er finger.\noo\nThe aborlglnees of Australia aro I\nsometimes regarded as the lowest hu\nman family.\nI TROUT m CHICKEN\nI SPECIAL DINNER\nHermitage\nHOTLL.\nJULY 24th. and 25th.\nOGDEN CANYON\nSS ,\"N\nWill Rogers, Star at the\nOgdeo Gives a Purse to\nthe Children's Hospital\nA trainload of easterners became\nquite mortified when they collected a\nhatful of money and presented it t\"\nWill Itogera, after he had done a bit\nof roping at the station In Santa Cruz,\nCalif where Rocors was at work on\nhis new Goldwyn picture. \"Jcs1 Oil\nMe Jim.\" now showing at the- Ogden\ntheatre Tlx- gum chewing expert of\nthe lariat was sitting lazily in his sad\ndle down at the depot when the east\nern train pulled in. Several of the'\ncow punchers with the company w'efo\nwith him, and as the train came to a\nstop Rogers started a little fancy rop\ning. He did his tricks and then took the\napplause. Some enthusiastic person\non the train took off hie hat and\ncried: \"Let's make up a little purSG\nfor this cowboy this is real western\nStuff I Ain t u great-\"'\nEverybody planked down a quarter\nor a half, and soon the hat was bulg\njing Just as the train started the en\nthused Individual presented It to smil\ning Rogers. Hill look It, cloffe.l bis\nhat and said: \"Guess this will help the\nchildren's hospital fund thanks!''\nI One of the cowpunohers yelled:\n\"Pretty good one on you, old tlm-\nr' \"1 his guy Is Will Rogers, an.i he\nmakes a salary of J-4.UO0 a week. He's\nhere making a picture now. Much\nobliged\"\nThe man who had taken up the col\nlection ducked into the smoking car\namid the Ha-ha's of the other passengers.\noo\nAIRSHIP GIVEN UP\nj LONDON. July 23 The German\nairship L 61. Islghtly larger than the\nBritish dirigible R-31 which lust year\nmade a trans Atlantic voyage v.iis\nj surrendered at the Pulham airdrome\n.in accordance with the terms of the\ntreaty of Versailles.\ni\nAfter you eat always use\nE ATONIC\n(FOR YOUR STOMACH'S SAKE)\none or two tablets eat like candy.\nInstantly' relieves Heartburn, Bloated\nI Gassy Feelinp. Stops indigestion,\nfood sourinjr, repeating, headacheand\ntho many miseriea caused by\nAcid-Stomach\nEATONIC is the beet remedy it takes\nI the harmful acids and leases right out\nI of the body and, of course, you get\nwell. Tens of thousands wonderfully\nbenefited. Guaranteed to satisfy or\nmoney refunded by your own dni\nI gi3t. Cost a trifle. \"Please try ltl\nL... i mm\npf HAS PRAISE\nFOR PROHIBITION\nSteel Head Declares There Is\na Growing Tendency to\nIncrease Savings\nNEW YORK, July 22 Prohibition\nhas been beneficial to the nation's ln\nj ilustrlal and economic lift, In the opln\nI Ion of Elbert H Gary, head of tho\nt'nited States Steel Corporation, who\nlsaued a statement here on the eve of\ndeparture for Europe, Riving his views\non tho business outlook generally.\n\"The prohibition laws have had\ni marked effect,\" he said in h'earls\nevery newspaper on- will road of fewer\nj in mates of prisons, alms houses and\nhospitals, and larger balances In sav\nings Institutions and better, cleaner\nri n 1 1 healthier conditions In the dwell\nings, all on account of prohibition.\nT. stimony on this subject is accumu\nlated day y day.\nFrom an economic pecuniary stand\npoint, 1 think a larger majority of the\npeople of this country are In favor of\nprohibition and It is pleasing to nof\nthat the largo numbers of Workmen,\nBO far as 1 am informed, subscribe to\nthis view.\nBl S1NESS SATISFACTION.\n\"Business conditions should be \"con\nMdored satisfactory V Mr Gary said,\ni although there has been \"a lack of\nprudence In business management\nsince the armistice,\" as regards to\nprices.\nThere seems to have been a dis\nposition on the part of the large nnm-\nbers, he added, \"to ask and accept\n'the highest prices which cou''\" Me ob\ntained Consequently, there has been\nj added to going prices tho amount\nwhich tho producer h- been obliged\nto pay, with profit on the whole, and\n(the purchaser has thus been obliged to\ncharge an increased price to his cus\ntomers\" Tho disposition to work and pro\nduce has been matcrln'i- diminished,\nI according to .Mr. Httry. He cited an\ninstance by which he said In order to\nremove and replace a headlight on a\nlocomotive \"it has been necessary to\nemploy four different men because of\nlabor regulations where one man\ni heretofore performed the &ame service\nI In less lime.\"\nI I I TI I s SSIBIjE.\n\"The rule has prevailed,\" he said,\n\"of doing as little work as possible\nand of securing as large pecuniary re-\nstilts as could be obtained However.\n.-\"in-uji.it to nn surprlsi- I have as\ni i-rtatne.i upon inquiry in the lat 30\nor 40 days, that labor at our various\nj plants Is more efficient per man than\nit has been at any time before dur\nl Inc the last five years.\"\nNo conflkt exists between capital\njand labor, he declared, troubles in the\npast having been between emplocrs\nand labor union leaders He referred\nI to the high wages being paid for\nj labor\n\"But It has not been paid too\nmuch,\" he continued. \"There have\nj been and are cases where compensa\ntion has been too low and work too\nstrenuous, b it I have been speaking of\nI the general rule. A majority of the\nemployers and employes read and 11s\nten attentive!\" to suggestions relating\ni to thoir obligations to all others, ln-\neluding the general public\"\ni Mr. Gary said the disposition to cut\nexpenditures and increase savings hv\nibeen noticeable of late and during the\niioxt few months thes tendencies lh\nI be more pronounced.\noo\nRoosevelt As\nA Speaker1\nFranklin P. Roosevelt. Democratic\n1 nominee for vice president. was\nsnapped recently, while on the speak\nJ ing platform. He Is well known an\nan orator\ni on 1\n00\nSTATION TO STUDY SUN\nWILL BE ESTABLISHED\n(N. E. A. Stafr Special)\n1 WASHINGTON. July pi. Perhaps\nB( i nee Is about to \"find a use for\nsun spots\nThese mysterious patches on the\nface of the sun have puzzled ob\nservers for years. Now it is believed\nthey Influence the weather and the\nSmithsonian institution is about to\nestablish n new sun observing sta\ntion in the llaqua Hala mountains in\nArizona, where clouds are rare.\nFor fifteen years observations of\nthe amount of heat reaching the\nearth from the sun (solar radiation)\nhas been carelully measured and\nSmithsonian scientists at Calama,\nChili, discovered that the ambunt va\nried constantly, due i0 sun spots and\nother changes in I he Burface of the\nsun\nThe. also found that these changes\nIn the complexion\" of Old Sol were\nfollowed in a few days by weather\nchanges on earth\noo\nNeit, a goddess In Egyptian\nlhulog. has the same characteristics\nBS Minerva.\nVIOLENT MATES\",\nlATTMJpDSI\nOutbreak on State Farm Is\nQuelled After One Insane\nNegro Is Shot Down\nBRIDGE WATER, Mass. July 2?,. B\nOne Inmate of the Brlilgewatr state M\nfarm was killed and three attendants n\nwere severely wounded with knives. 3H\nduring an outbreak by inmates of the B\nviolent ward this afternoon Lloyd I B\nKingdom, a npro inmatr was ahot Ljg\nand killed by officers. Antonio Dis- B\nrest, who was associated with King- B\ndom in the outbreak, war. captured un- Bj\nThe trouble occurred when 30 in- JM\nmates of the violent ward were being Bl\nlet Into the yard. All but Kingdom and H\nDlsrest li.nl gone out when tho two HJ\nturned upon th ntten'.lants and slash- H\ned them with knives which had come H\nInto their possession In some unknown H\nmanner. w',\nKingdom and Dlsrest fled upstairs PE\nto a ward room where, surrounded\nby hospital attendants and prison off I- j\nleers, made a dash for the stairs They H\nrefused to halt and it was then that ESJ\nKingdom was shot\nDDROTHY DALTOEV IS I\nWHILE 1\nSCENES ABE FILMED g\n\"The Dark Mirror\" Requires H\nPretty Star to Invade\nChinatown Cafes\nDorothy Dalton didn't altogether I\nenjoy making some of the scenes for; fS\nher latest Thomas II nee picture.\nThe Dark Mirror,\" which will be II\"' I\nattraction at th Alhambra the. are to- m\nday and tomorrow According to lhO !g\nstory. Miss Dalton ha6 the role of ai\nNew York Bociet) irl who is kid- I\nnaped by a gang of thugs bees I8\nShe Closely resembles their leader's' (i9\nsweetheart. The action required scenes u\nto be made in dlvca In the slums of) m\nVow Vork, most of them In the\nChinatown underworld\n\"We Spent several nights at one of 9\ntho famous cafes rm the Bowery.\" S\nsaid Miss Dalton, discussing the pic- fl\nture. \"The camera was can full con- M\ncealed, and I don't think any of the I E\nfrequenters of the place suspected\nwho we were. I was having a good I K3\ntime, though It required me to munch RH\non a soscy sandwich and drink sonu- M\nnondescript liquid that was .-aippo.s. il\nto be beer, but wasn't. fv\nSuddenly I looked around and a 88\nrough fellow with all tho earmarks of H\na thug was staring at me. Catching i M\nmy eye, h- Bmlied a little wicked grin ja\nI think ho was w ise t,. us. But 1 didn't H\nstay to find out. I insisted to Mr Gib- Kuj\nlyn. our director, that we leave ,,t Eg\nonce ah the waj uptown I had a I H\nfeeling that the evil-looking nian wasiH\ntoll iwing u ami it was with a feeling By\nof relief that J found m.vs?lf alone In 1 14\nmy lln i b part menl f:,i\n\"The Dark Mirror\" was adapted H\nfrom Ixiuis Joseph Vance's novel of Bj\nthe same name. It is a I'aramount H\nArtcraft picture. f A\nCOUNTY CHARGE WILL GET f\nSPLENDOR AT FUNERAL\nSAX JOSE. Cal July 23 A thirtyrIH\npiece band w ill be in attendance at the E9\nluneral of .lo.se Castro, age.l iimiap Ppj\nof the county hospital here. whose fSfi\nbody was found In a iond In n down- jwi\ntown pari; l'\"ie years ago. it became Ek\nknown following disco verey of the tE\nbody, Castro deposited in a local bank W\nmoney to cover his funeral expenses' mi\nand contracted with an undertaker to IS\nprovide a thirty-piece band and a RE\nnearse drawn by six white horses lw\nOwing to the dearth of white hoi.-. &v\ntho undertaker will be unable to com- SB\ni with thai pari of ins contract. An jQ\nautomobile hearse will be substituted JP!\n00 t w\nANTI-SALOONISTS WILL\nSHOW CANDIDATES'RECORD\nV.SHINGTON Julj it The Mill- BB\nSaloon League '.'t America will not in- H\ndorse any presidential camlidate for 9\nelection thi-i year, hut has ordered a\ncompilation of facts as to the prohlbl- tm\ntiou record and present Stand of each I\nI candidate and will make this public. S\nThis announcement was made bs the S\nexecutive committee of tht organixa- M\ntiiii alter in aM-il-iv ses.slon In which W\nsuperin